1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:27,135
namo tassa bhagavato hara-hatto samma-sambhodassa namo tassa bhagavato hara-hatto samma-sambhodassa namo tassa bhagavato hara-hatto samma-sambhodassa

2
00:00:27,114 --> 00:00:33,990
Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-awakened one.

3
00:00:34,290 --> 00:00:43,432
So, I've chosen this topic of courage, but I mean, really, what we're talking about is fear, isn't it?

4
00:00:43,591 --> 00:00:44,954
Overcoming fear.

5
00:00:46,960 --> 00:00:56,295
Now, fear is, I would argue, is the most fundamental of our emotional states dependent on delusion.

6
00:00:56,414 --> 00:00:56,835
Yeah.

7
00:00:56,856 --> 00:01:05,609
So this delusion of a self, it's created a self which feels uncertain because, you know, sickness, aging and death and all that.

8
00:01:05,590 --> 00:01:13,403
And therefore, it has this fear about itself and it reacts to this fear by making itself safe.

9
00:01:13,743 --> 00:01:16,007
And that's when we start accumulating stuff.

10
00:01:16,649 --> 00:01:18,512
So money makes us feel safe.

11
00:01:18,531 --> 00:01:26,325
We've got a big bank account, lots of friends and power, of course, and lots of pleasurable things to do.

12
00:01:26,486 --> 00:01:29,792
So we keep our mind off these horrible things.

13
00:01:29,772 --> 00:01:40,623
So this fear of death or fear of sickness, et cetera, aging and all that, it has this effect of making us try to escape it.

14
00:01:41,385 --> 00:01:53,057
And of course, this is one of the great awakeners that this was the awakener, the awakeners that drove the Buddha to seek liberation, sickness, aging and death.

15
00:01:53,897 --> 00:01:58,462
So it plays a big, obviously plays a big part in our lives.

16
00:01:59,152 --> 00:02:10,081
And it shapes our behavior, you know, when we're in any situation which is dangerous or stressful or in any way a challenge.

17
00:02:11,043 --> 00:02:13,305
So it's something we need to deal with.

18
00:02:13,384 --> 00:02:15,667
And I'm sure all of you have to some extent or other.

19
00:02:17,109 --> 00:02:23,335
And it won't go, you see, until the very last moment when the self is destroyed.

20
00:02:23,455 --> 00:02:26,037
So it's going to be with us for a while.

21
00:02:26,405 --> 00:02:28,647
And we have to see it as a friend.

22
00:02:28,668 --> 00:02:31,572
I mean, after all, it is trying to protect us, right?

23
00:02:32,152 --> 00:02:33,555
And so we have to give it a hug.

24
00:02:34,276 --> 00:02:41,044
And then we have to sort of open up to it, get the feel of it, and not run away from it.

25
00:02:41,686 --> 00:02:47,112
So, of course, that running away from it is the panic, isn't it?

26
00:02:48,409 --> 00:03:03,784
So if we consider the amount of fear that we have as a measure of the delusion of self, every time we undermine this fear, we're undermining the delusion of self, right?

27
00:03:03,805 --> 00:03:05,045
So there is a plus to it.

28
00:03:05,747 --> 00:03:13,373
And in fact, the Buddha in the Dhammapada, verse 39, tells us that in the end, all fear would disappear.

29
00:03:13,493 --> 00:03:14,534
This is what he says.

30
00:03:15,949 --> 00:03:30,062
For one who has awakened, whose mind isn't agitated, whose heart isn't tormented, and who has abandoned both merit and demerit, fear does not exist.

31
00:03:30,723 --> 00:03:45,956
So once the mind has been silenced and the heart calmed, and there's no attempt to create karma based on a self, me creating stuff,

32
00:03:46,358 --> 00:03:48,700
Fear is completely gone.

33
00:03:49,241 --> 00:03:51,185
So the prognosis is good.

34
00:03:51,384 --> 00:03:52,947
This is what we have to keep remembering.

35
00:03:55,670 --> 00:04:01,979
Now, psychologists have delineated six areas of experience where we experience fear.

36
00:04:02,019 --> 00:04:09,109
And I'm indebted to Gwen for this, who runs the monthly meeting on climate change, climate crisis.

37
00:04:09,460 --> 00:04:16,197
So it's the physical, the social, moral, emotional, intellectual, and spiritual.

38
00:04:16,478 --> 00:04:20,988
This is sometimes where we need to find a certain level of courage.

39
00:04:21,543 --> 00:04:30,016
So the physical, I think, is pretty straightforward, you know, just straightforward with the fear of pain, fear of debilitating illness, etc.

40
00:04:30,898 --> 00:04:40,853
So whenever that touches us, we come across this fear and it's being able to sit with the fear, allow it to arise, pass away.

41
00:04:41,194 --> 00:04:43,298
That's the courage, the internal courage.

42
00:04:44,154 --> 00:04:48,120
Of course, some people have to find that physical courage in daily life.

43
00:04:49,682 --> 00:04:51,004
You know, I'm thinking of sports.

44
00:04:51,324 --> 00:04:54,809
A lot of sports demand physical courage, especially boxing.

45
00:04:55,990 --> 00:05:02,377
I don't know if any of you have done a bit of boxing, but you definitely got to have a bit of physical courage there.

46
00:05:03,038 --> 00:05:06,163
And then there are occupations, you know, soldiering.

47
00:05:06,581 --> 00:05:13,430
If we think of what's happening now in the Ukraine, both sides demands a physical courage.

48
00:05:13,711 --> 00:05:15,574
Even the police sometimes need that.

49
00:05:16,514 --> 00:05:20,740
So this identity with the body is profound.

50
00:05:20,800 --> 00:05:21,141
Yeah.

51
00:05:21,161 --> 00:05:23,064
I mean, you can't be here without one.

52
00:05:23,324 --> 00:05:28,310
So, I mean, it's the physical representation of our existence.

53
00:05:29,351 --> 00:05:33,197
So it's important that we

54
00:05:33,548 --> 00:05:48,333
Whenever these whenever this comes to us that we really turn towards it, see it as a friend, see it that it's actually trying to protect us and allow get get almost get comfortable with the feelings of fear.

55
00:05:48,634 --> 00:05:49,696
That's that's the big thing.

56
00:05:49,995 --> 00:05:52,300
Not not to not to push it away.

57
00:05:54,439 --> 00:05:59,446
So we may use that as a sort of questions of ourselves.

58
00:05:59,526 --> 00:06:05,172
Has there been a time in our lives when we've been physically timid, when we should have done something?

59
00:06:07,194 --> 00:06:08,516
And how do we feel about that?

60
00:06:08,555 --> 00:06:11,298
Is there some guilt and shame that we haven't worked through?

61
00:06:13,422 --> 00:06:22,151
And then, you know, to make these silent inward resolutions that if it's demanded of us, we'll do our best to manifest courage.

62
00:06:23,684 --> 00:06:25,567
So that's the physical part.

63
00:06:26,648 --> 00:06:32,396
The social part, usually it's to do with feeling embarrassed in a meeting.

64
00:06:32,415 --> 00:06:37,182
So you don't want to ask a question in case people think it's silly and stuff like that.

65
00:06:38,244 --> 00:06:44,351
So we're afraid of criticism, saying something which other people will jump down our throats for, things like that.

66
00:06:46,095 --> 00:06:51,581
Even sort of expressing ourselves to neighbours, to a neighbour who...

67
00:06:51,562 --> 00:06:55,908
whom you know has a different opinion or a different understanding.

68
00:06:57,370 --> 00:07:06,583
So that sort of social courage is sometimes, you know, sometimes that really we have to try to express.

69
00:07:07,865 --> 00:07:14,194
So, I mean, obviously we have great examples of that, you know, Martin Luther King, Nelson Mandela.

70
00:07:14,173 --> 00:07:23,610
All these people who are out on demonstrations, which are getting to be more and more policed and more danger of being fined and sent to prison.

71
00:07:24,973 --> 00:07:32,807
And of course, when you think of countries and the amount of courage you need, like, for instance, that terrible time in Iran.

72
00:07:33,411 --> 00:07:44,790
where the morality police murdered that young woman and the tremendous repressive measures that the government took, you know, even capturing, you know, capturing people and then hanging them.

73
00:07:46,093 --> 00:07:47,596
We've got, of course, Russia.

74
00:07:47,916 --> 00:07:52,904
So you've got a man called Kara Murza.

75
00:07:53,122 --> 00:07:59,531
who is a political activist, journalist, author, filmmaker, political prisoner.

76
00:07:59,992 --> 00:08:03,959
So he spoke against the present war and he's ended up in jail for 25 years.

77
00:08:04,338 --> 00:08:08,485
And unless Putin is somehow got rid of, he's going to be there for 25 years.

78
00:08:08,906 --> 00:08:15,096
And then, of course, there's that Russian opposition leader, Navalny, who's, I think, tremendously courageous.

79
00:08:15,336 --> 00:08:19,702
It's unbelievable, really, whom Putin actually tried to poison.

80
00:08:21,607 --> 00:08:27,432
Even if you look back into Russian history, the misery of the Russians is unbelievable.

81
00:08:28,233 --> 00:08:30,855
I don't think it's quite remarkable.

82
00:08:31,437 --> 00:08:47,412
And yet they find this courage through, if you remember Stalin's time when the Samizdat, when they were writing poems and all sorts of stuff and passing it on bits of paper to friends, trying to keep the resistance alive.

83
00:08:50,243 --> 00:08:55,267
And of course, there's the investigative journalist, the 67 being murdered last year.

84
00:08:56,528 --> 00:09:04,174
The most prominent, of course, was when the Israeli forces shot, murdered Shireen Abu Akleh in the occupied West Bank.

85
00:09:04,195 --> 00:09:05,456
It's awful, awful, awful.

86
00:09:06,596 --> 00:09:09,620
So again, it's just, you know, social courage.

87
00:09:09,639 --> 00:09:19,609
It's again an opportunity for us to contemplate where, you know, we haven't made our views known out of fear, out of fear of criticism or whatever.

88
00:09:20,095 --> 00:09:44,583
being mocked attacked and again there might be some shame or guilt around that so you have to work through it you know you have to allow it to come up and uh and then to make that resolution you know should i find myself in such a situation i'll i'll make my understandings known yeah sort of shading into that is moral courage um

89
00:09:45,509 --> 00:09:47,692
It's more to do with right and wrong.

90
00:09:48,072 --> 00:09:54,740
And I'm reminded now of the 60s, which, of course, is prehistoric now.

91
00:09:55,360 --> 00:10:05,993
But we had a person in the UK called Mary Whitehouse who really led the charge against the loss of moral compass.

92
00:10:07,014 --> 00:10:12,039
In those days, it was called permissiveness, and people were getting very upset about it.

93
00:10:12,610 --> 00:10:14,491
And of course, we did lose the moral ground.

94
00:10:15,894 --> 00:10:25,886
We found out about the behavior of the famous DJ, Jimmy Savile, and then the Catholic priests and all that, and pedophiles.

95
00:10:25,907 --> 00:10:38,482
So it was all, I mean, there was something happened in the 60s which sort of took away a grounding that we used to have as a society in morality.

96
00:10:39,543 --> 00:10:42,827
But of course, these situations are never absolutely white and black.

97
00:10:43,188 --> 00:10:45,251
It's quite difficult to decide.

98
00:10:46,553 --> 00:10:51,542
Then we have things like abortion, which in Europe is now sort of a dead subject, really.

99
00:10:52,222 --> 00:10:58,614
But we can see the tremendous war that's going on in the United States over it.

100
00:10:58,634 --> 00:11:06,866
And the usual sort of battle between the mother's rights and the right of the fetus.

101
00:11:07,623 --> 00:11:16,033
And I think more upfront these days for us is immigration and the impact it's having on society.

102
00:11:17,054 --> 00:11:18,537
And no one has a clue.

103
00:11:18,736 --> 00:11:25,605
I mean, I haven't a clue as to what the answer is to the growing level of immigration.

104
00:11:26,086 --> 00:11:31,133
And when climate change really begins to bite, presumably it's going to get much worse.

105
00:11:31,770 --> 00:11:36,135
So these people are coming out of areas of abject poverty and almost unlivable.

106
00:11:36,797 --> 00:11:41,722
And on top of that, there's the political refugees.

107
00:11:43,664 --> 00:11:57,581
So, of course, the danger here is that it pushes society to, the indigenous society, we can say, to defend itself and move over towards fascist regimes, which is happening.

108
00:11:57,681 --> 00:12:00,264
You know, we've got Orban in Poland.

109
00:12:00,303 --> 00:12:01,625
We've got

110
00:12:01,605 --> 00:12:04,129
was Maloney in Italy.

111
00:12:05,730 --> 00:12:15,543
And this comes out of fear, you know, but it's something that if we want to maintain a liberal society, it's something we really have to tackle.

112
00:12:16,203 --> 00:12:21,370
So again, there's this whole area of morality which demands courage.

113
00:12:22,471 --> 00:12:28,879
And, you know, has there been a time in the past we could have been more morally courageous?

114
00:12:30,547 --> 00:12:32,289
And again, to make that resolution.

115
00:12:34,933 --> 00:12:36,878
The next one is the emotional courage.

116
00:12:36,898 --> 00:12:44,149
Well, that points to opening up to these very difficult mental states that we have within ourselves.

117
00:12:44,750 --> 00:12:49,077
And that's, of course, very much part of our practice of vipassana.

118
00:12:49,260 --> 00:13:12,534
just to allow, you know, very difficult mental states to arise and to be able to see the aversion that we have to it, the fear that we have to it, and just to allow that to pass away, you know, and then just to sit quietly with it, to sort of sink into the fire, tie ourselves to the bonfire and just allow it to rage.

119
00:13:12,514 --> 00:13:15,700
And we do that because that's the healing.

120
00:13:15,779 --> 00:13:29,663
Once these emotions have a chance to liberate themselves, of course, what we mistake is that when we begin to create these stories in the mind and it feels like a relief,

121
00:13:29,913 --> 00:13:41,845
If you're angry and you go off onto a fantasy of beating somebody up, then it feels like a relief, but actually it's just exercised the anger.

122
00:13:42,326 --> 00:13:48,052
It's when you feel it as a physical sensation that it's actually being released.

123
00:13:48,072 --> 00:13:50,934
So this, of course, we know through our Vipassana.

124
00:13:52,035 --> 00:13:58,182
And there's a little passage here that I've copied from the Buddha who had to tackle fear.

125
00:13:58,616 --> 00:14:02,341
when he first went out into the jungles.

126
00:14:03,403 --> 00:14:13,155
And while I was staying there, a wild animal would come or a peacock would make a twig fall.

127
00:14:13,677 --> 00:14:19,684
The wind would rustle the falling leaves and the thought would occur to me, is this that fear and terror coming?

128
00:14:20,265 --> 00:14:24,912
And then the thought occurred to me, why do I just keep waiting for fear and terror?

129
00:14:25,870 --> 00:14:28,154
So instead of that, this is what he determines.

130
00:14:28,876 --> 00:14:38,580
What if I, in whatever state I'm in, when fear and terror come to me, were to subdue that fear and terror in that very state?

131
00:14:38,745 --> 00:14:46,298
So when fear and terror came to me while I was walking backwards and forwards, I would not sit down or stand or lie down.

132
00:14:46,458 --> 00:14:51,989
I would keep walking backwards and forward until I had pacified the fear and terror.

133
00:14:52,610 --> 00:14:57,639
When fear and terror came to me while I was standing, I would not walk or sit or lie down.

134
00:14:58,340 --> 00:15:02,947
I would keep standing until I had subdued the fear and terror.

135
00:15:03,197 --> 00:15:07,746
And when fear and terror came to me while sitting, I would not lie down or stand up or walk.

136
00:15:07,868 --> 00:15:11,755
I would keep sitting until I had subdued that fear and terror.

137
00:15:12,277 --> 00:15:19,350
When terror and fear came to me while I was lying down, I would not sit up or stand or walk.

138
00:15:19,431 --> 00:15:23,620
I'd keep lying down until I had subdued the fear and terror.

139
00:15:23,600 --> 00:15:28,437
So, in other words, he turned towards it.

140
00:15:29,140 --> 00:15:33,356
The word subdue does suggest some sort of suppression, but that's not what he means.

141
00:15:36,003 --> 00:15:53,748
So again, you know, if we have a specific mental state that arises that we find very difficult, you know, to find, you know, if it comes up at a convenient time when it's just you by yourself, whatever, just to be able to move into it and stay with it.

142
00:15:56,672 --> 00:15:58,234
And then there's the intellectual.

143
00:15:59,115 --> 00:16:02,500
So here, oops, just a minute, we've got something wrong here.

144
00:16:03,509 --> 00:16:05,714
Then there's the intellectual.

145
00:16:05,815 --> 00:16:13,312
So recently here in the UK, we had a Professor Kathleen Stock, who's a philosopher and a gender critical academic.

146
00:16:14,436 --> 00:16:18,886
And she's been hounded out of the university that she worked in.

147
00:16:19,870 --> 00:16:20,792
And there was a whole...

148
00:16:21,548 --> 00:16:26,815
rumpus at Oxford University, asking her to be cancelled.

149
00:16:28,216 --> 00:16:38,730
And she basically stated in her book that trans women are not, it's difficult to say, are not the same as born women.

150
00:16:38,770 --> 00:16:40,013
Let's put it that way.

151
00:16:40,701 --> 00:16:42,304
So that's created quite a rumpus.

152
00:16:42,845 --> 00:16:46,390
And of course, she lost the job and everything from it.

153
00:16:47,072 --> 00:16:58,230
So this whole area is one where people have to have the courage to speak their truth, you might say.

154
00:16:59,452 --> 00:17:04,059
It's a sort of dodgy area because it depends which way you're looking at it.

155
00:17:04,494 --> 00:17:18,692
One of the paradoxes of this particular argument is nobody complains about a woman who becomes a man, changes her gender to a male.

156
00:17:19,734 --> 00:17:24,220
And I presume that because there's not much problem with that.

157
00:17:24,340 --> 00:17:31,650
So if a trans man walks into a male toilet, it's not a problem for the men.

158
00:17:31,933 --> 00:17:39,480
And if they happen to be in the same sport, you know, boxing or something like that, it wouldn't be a big problem for men.

159
00:17:39,915 --> 00:17:50,893
But on the other side, it's obviously some women feel threatened by it, you know, in hospitals, in toilets and in sport, you know.

160
00:17:50,952 --> 00:17:56,560
So it's a difficult area, difficult area.

161
00:17:56,961 --> 00:18:05,775
And we need to think about it because there may come a time that we have to express our views, our opinions and feel free to do so.

162
00:18:06,516 --> 00:18:09,180
I mean, here in the West, you know, we have that freedom.

163
00:18:10,779 --> 00:18:26,800
Interestingly enough, I just got here, in Hindu or Buddhist countries, and I think also true in the Far East, there isn't this obsession with sex at all, you know.

164
00:18:27,702 --> 00:18:33,210
And the funny thing is that

165
00:18:34,134 --> 00:18:46,535
In the East, Buddhist especially, there's a sort of myth that you're much better off to become enlightened if you happen to be born a man.

166
00:18:47,175 --> 00:18:53,005
So many women make the determination to be born a man in the next lifetime.

167
00:18:54,097 --> 00:19:01,965
And there was a case in Sri Lanka, which is the opposite, where a Catholic bishop became a Buddhist.

168
00:19:02,826 --> 00:19:12,258
And towards the end of his life, this is, I think, going back to the 60s, 50s, 60s, towards the end of his life, he determined that he wanted to be reborn as a woman.

169
00:19:12,778 --> 00:19:20,105
So he began dressing as a woman and sort of trying to change his gender before he died.

170
00:19:21,352 --> 00:19:38,074
Anyway, it really is just a case intellectually of, you know, really being able to hold our views and opinions just a bit more lightly to see them more as perspective.

171
00:19:38,974 --> 00:19:44,642
If you hold on to your views and opinions too strongly, you know, I'm right and everybody else is wrong.

172
00:19:45,027 --> 00:19:46,528
then there's always conflict.

173
00:19:47,530 --> 00:19:58,326
But to be able to be open to critique, to have your views challenged, even nuanced, I mean, that really takes courage.

174
00:19:58,346 --> 00:20:01,131
And then finally, we have the spiritual courage.

175
00:20:01,692 --> 00:20:10,365
And there's one little example here, which I think it really affected me when I found this out.

176
00:20:10,885 --> 00:20:13,869
When the Inquisition started,

177
00:20:13,916 --> 00:20:20,084
and they attacked the Cathars, the Albigensians, down in the south of France.

178
00:20:20,124 --> 00:20:21,806
What's today is the south of France.

179
00:20:22,826 --> 00:20:36,422
There was an occasion where about some escaped from the first town that was attacked in Béziers, and they ended up in a place called Minerves, which was a heavily well-fortified small town with a river running through it, etc.

180
00:20:37,182 --> 00:20:42,709
And there was a certain Simon de Montfort, who was really quite a cruel soldier.

181
00:20:42,689 --> 00:20:51,602
Anyway, they were eventually conquered and he just kept lobbing stones at them, you know, with a catapult.

182
00:20:52,425 --> 00:21:04,602
Anyway, when they finally collapsed and they entered into the town, they built a big bonfire and 140 Cathars threw themselves onto the flames.

183
00:21:05,623 --> 00:21:07,326
That's courageous.

184
00:21:08,166 --> 00:21:16,557
And ironically, there is a monument to that right in front of the Catholic Church.

185
00:21:17,679 --> 00:21:19,682
So that's a bit cheeky.

186
00:21:21,535 --> 00:21:31,851
So in our actual spiritual practice, there is, remember, this whole process of renunciation, of letting go, letting go, letting go.

187
00:21:32,491 --> 00:21:38,000
And really, this idea of nibbana, you know, it's a sort of shady idea.

188
00:21:38,060 --> 00:21:40,484
The Buddha tells us it's the highest happiness.

189
00:21:40,565 --> 00:21:43,509
It's absolutely you want it when you've got it.

190
00:21:43,490 --> 00:21:45,294
But we don't know what it is.

191
00:21:45,674 --> 00:21:51,167
And in the Christian tradition, they talk of the mysterium tremendum and fascinens.

192
00:21:51,648 --> 00:21:56,700
So it's the mystery which is both frightening, makes you tremble, and yet it fascinates you.

193
00:21:56,760 --> 00:22:00,469
Yet you want to find out what it is.

194
00:22:00,449 --> 00:22:06,395
So it's going to take some courage because it's like you're walking backwards towards a cliff.

195
00:22:06,415 --> 00:22:08,179
You know, there's a drop coming somewhere.

196
00:22:08,439 --> 00:22:15,146
You know, you've got to let go of everything at some point, but you don't know when it's coming and you haven't a clue what's going to happen when you actually fall off the cliff.

197
00:22:16,009 --> 00:22:26,000
So there's a bit of anxiety, fear, existential anxiety around the whole process of spiritual practice.

198
00:22:28,411 --> 00:22:33,103
So again, whenever that sort of fear comes up, we just turn to it.

199
00:22:33,143 --> 00:22:34,605
The usual thing, give a hug.

200
00:22:34,625 --> 00:22:39,898
It's only trying to protect us and make a determination to continue with our practice.

201
00:22:40,842 --> 00:22:44,631
So these six areas just give us a way of examining ourselves.

202
00:22:44,611 --> 00:22:49,118
The whole idea of timidity when fear comes and courage.

203
00:22:49,720 --> 00:22:54,008
There is another side to this, which I'll tackle on another talk.

204
00:22:54,028 --> 00:22:58,195
And that, of course, is the courage of forbearance, the courage of patience.

205
00:22:58,757 --> 00:23:00,460
And the Buddha has a lot to say about that.

206
00:23:05,096 --> 00:23:06,779
Yeah, very good.

207
00:23:07,421 --> 00:23:25,131
So I can only hope my words have been of some assistance, that I have not caused confusion, and that by your ability to stay with fear, to overcome fear, you will be liberated from all suffering sooner rather than later.

